3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates funding rates hourly based on the difference between the perpetual contract price and the oracle price from Chainlink. Funding payments occur every hour at the top of the hour, with rates typically ranging from -0.01% to 0.01% per hour. The oracle-based system reduces funding rate volatility compared to order book exchanges, as it doesn't rely on mark-to-index calculations. Long positions pay short positions when funding is positive, with payments processed automatically through the smart contract."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","XRP","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"XRP/USDT on GMX benefits from consistent oracle pricing that often differs from spot market volatility, creating predictable funding rate patterns. The pair's high liquidity and moderate volatility make it suitable for funding rate arbitrage, especially when compared to CEX rates. GMX's hourly funding frequency provides more opportunities for rate capture compared to 8-hour cycles on traditional exchanges."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical XRP Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"XRP funding rates on GMX typically oscillate between -0.005% and 0.005% per hour, with periods of sustained positive funding during bullish XRP sentiment. Historical data shows funding rates tend to spike during XRP regulatory news events, often reaching 0.01% hourly when retail sentiment drives long bias. The oracle-based pricing creates smoother funding transitions compared to order book DEXs, with less extreme rate spikes. GMX's hourly settlement means daily funding costs can accumulate to 0.12-0.24% during high volatility periods."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Funding rate arbitrage on GMX involves taking opposite positions across CEXs with 8-hour funding cycles and GMX's hourly cycle. Traders can capture rate differentials by shorting XRP on GMX when funding is positive while holding spot XRP or going long on CEXs with negative funding. The oracle pricing mechanism often creates temporary disconnects from spot prices, generating additional alpha beyond pure funding rate capture. Position sizing must account for GMX's 0.05-0.07% trading fees and potential price impact on large orders through the GLP pools."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Mitigation"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Oracle dependency represents the primary risk, as Chainlink feed failures could impact position valuations and funding calculations. Price impact through GLP pools can be significant for large XRP positions, potentially offsetting funding rate gains on size. GMX's smart contract risk and Arbitrum bridge dependencies add additional layers compared to centralized exchanges. Traders should monitor GLP utilization rates, as high utilization can increase borrowing costs and affect position profitability beyond funding payments."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often are XRP funding payments settled on GMX?","answer":"XRP funding payments on GMX are settled every hour at the top of the hour. This differs from most CEXs that use 8-hour cycles, providing more frequent opportunities to capture funding rate changes."},{"question":"What happens if Chainlink's XRP price feed fails on GMX?","answer":"GMX uses multiple oracle sources and has fallback mechanisms, but prolonged oracle failures could freeze new positions or force settlement at last known prices. Existing positions remain open but funding calculations may pause until feeds resume."},{"question":"Can I hedge XRP funding exposure using GLP tokens?","answer":"GLP tokens provide exposure to the entire GMX liquidity pool including XRP, so they don't offer direct hedge capabilities. However, GLP yields can offset some trading costs when combined with XRP perpetual strategies."},{"question":"How does GMX's XRP funding rate compare to Binance or Bybit?","answer":"GMX's hourly funding typically shows less volatility than CEX 8-hour rates due to oracle smoothing. However, daily cumulative funding can exceed CEX rates during trending periods, making cross-exchange arbitrage potentially profitable."}]}]
